# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2026-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The **2026 Commonwealth Games**, officially known as the **XXIII Commonwealth Games** and commonly known as **Glasgow 2026**, is a planned multi-sport event scheduled from 23 July to 2 August 2026, to be hosted in Glasgow, the largest city in Scotland, for members of the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This will be the fourth Commonwealth Games to be hosted in Scotland, following the 1970 and 1986 games in Edinburgh, and the 2014 Games in Glasgow.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The 2026 Commonwealth Games will be the first to be held since the death of Queen Elizabeth II and the accession of King Charles III as Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This will be the first edition since Donald Rukare became president of the Commonwealth Games Federation (CGF).
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] For some time, the Games were without a host after the Australian state of Victoria withdrew, having initially been announced as the host in April 2022.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 18 July 2023, the Victorian state government cancelled its plans due to escalating cost projections.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The city of Gold Coast, Queensland, briefly offered to co-host the event but later withdrew for similar reasons.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] With no host, there was a risk that the Games might be postponed to 2027 or cancelled entirely.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 11 August 2024, reports surfaced that Glasgow had reached an agreement to take over the hosting rights, but the next day it was clarified that talks were ongoing with no final agreement or imminent announcement.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Commonwealth Games Scotland proposed a scaled-back version of the event, featuring 10 to 13 sports and using existing infrastructure, with £100 million in funding from the CGF and an additional £30 to 50 million from commercial sources, ensuring no significant public funds would be required.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] A further update on 30 August 2024 confirmed that the Games would be primarily funded by AU$200 million, secured as compensation from the Victorian government following their withdrawal.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 17 September 2024, it was announced that the Scottish Government had agreed to host the games with financial backing from Commonwealth Games Australia.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The scaled-down and low-cost Games will feature 10 sports taking place over seven venues and no athletes' village.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] A new model called CGF Partnerships (CGFP) was implemented which aimed to give stronger support to the associations and cities that show interests in hosting future Games and enhance the overall value of the event.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This is similar to the process used by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) since 2017.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] In 2015, the South African city of Durban originally won the rights to host the 2022 Commonwealth Games, but was stripped of this right in 2017 due to financial concerns.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] As a result, Birmingham moved up its planned Games from 2026 to 2022.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This left the 2026 Games without a host and bids from Kuala Lumpur, Cardiff, Calgary, Edmonton and Adelaide were all withdrawn due to concerns over costs, with a hosting decision not made by the Commonwealth Games Federation between 2019 and 2022.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] In January 2022, the Victorian State Government announced it was giving serious consideration to a late request from the CGF to host the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 16 February 2022, Premier of Victoria Daniel Andrews confirmed that the state was in exclusive negotiations with the CGF to host the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It was stated that if successful in hosting the Games a second time, a Victorian bid would aim to emphasise the state's regional centres—such as Geelong, Ballarat and Bendigo—as opposed to being predominantly Melbourne-based, such as in 2006.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Bendigo had previously hosted the 2004 Commonwealth Youth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Acceptance of the bid would likely also be conditional upon agreement on ways to control costs, such as housing athletes and officials in hotels rather than a dedicated village.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This bid was confirmed as successful on 12 April 2022.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 18 July 2023, Andrews and Deputy Premier Jacinta Allan announced the state government intended to cancel the 2026 Victorian Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Fifteen months after agreeing to host the Games, the Premier said the cost had escalated to an estimated A$6–7 billion, double the estimated economic benefits for the state, and the government could not justify the expense.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The state said it would terminate its host agreement with the Commonwealth Games Federation and seek a settlement of the contract.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The withdrawal prompted a new search for a host for the 2026 Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The Mayor of London Sadiq Khan subsequently said he was "ready" to support the London bid to replace Victoria as the host.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The First Minister of Scotland Humza Yousaf also stated that he was "willing to consider proposals" for Scotland to host at least some of the events at the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 4 December 2023, the Gold Coast ruled itself out of hosting the games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 11 March 2024, the Olympic Council of Malaysia revealed that the Commonwealth Games Federation (CGF) had offered Malaysia approximately £100 million to host the 2026 Commonwealth Games on a smaller scale than initially planned, with discussions ongoing.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] However, on 22 March 2024, the Malaysian Cabinet declined the offer, stating that the £100 million would be insufficient to cover the event's costs.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Furthermore, the Federal Government was unwilling to use taxpayers' money to fund the games, especially given the risk of a scheduling clash with the 2027 SEA Games, also set to be held in Malaysia.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 14 March 2024, the Singapore National Olympic Council (SNOC), Sport Singapore (SportSG), and Commonwealth Games Singapore (CGS) announced they were exploring the feasibility of hosting the games, including the possibility of a joint proposal with Malaysia to reduce expenses.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] However, on 3 April 2024, CGS and SportSG confirmed that Singapore would not submit a bid.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 11 April 2024, it was announced that Glasgow was considered as a "last possibility" to host the 2026 Games in the event, if no other host was forthcoming, in an alternative to safeguard the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It was reported that the Games would be in a smaller scale and could reuse venues from the 2014 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Accommodation for the athletes would comprise hotels, and possibly a combination of Glasgow Caledonian University and University of Glasgow student residences.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Furthermore, the costs of the Games would be covered fully by the Commonwealth Games Federation and their other corporate sponsors.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Discussions were ongoing between Commonwealth Games Scotland, the Scottish Government, and EventScotland with a confirmed bid expected by the end of the month.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] However, the bid documents would not end up being submitted at that time.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 25 July 2024, the BBC reported that a decision would be made in August.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 11 August 2024, it was speculated that an agreement was reached for Glasgow to take over the hosting rights of the games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] A statement from the Commonwealth Games Council for Scotland issued on 30 August 2024, suggested a compact and low scale games concept with 10 sports across four venues including the Scotstoun Stadium and the Tollcross International Swimming Centre.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 17 September 2024, it was announced that the Scottish Government had agreed to host the Games with compensation from Victoria.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The King's Baton was officially launched on 10 March 2025, to mark the start of the 500 days countdown, with King Charles III handing over the baton to the first runner, Sir Chris Hoy.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The baton made from ash wood was designed by Tim Norman.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The organisation decided that he would be sent to the Caribbean region to start the global relay with Port of Spain, in Trinidad and Tobago, as the first international stop.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The choice of Trinidad and Tobago was as a result of the country successfully hosting the 2023 Commonwealth Youth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] For the 18th Baton Relay, a new format was introduced where each of the 74 Commonwealth Games Associations (CGAs) received an individual baton crafted in Glasgow.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Rather than passing a single baton between nations, each CGA was permitted to customise its baton to reflect its local culture.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The change also altered the logistics of the relay, replacing the traditional international transfer of a single object with localised events.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] This adjustment was intended to reduce fuel consumption and transport disruptions while allowing each CGA up to six days to host local activities.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Thanks to this format, this iteration became the longest and most decentralised relay in the event's history.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Additionally to being the first time of being part of The King's Baton Relay, Commonwealth Sport partnered with the Royal Commonwealth Society (RCS) to integrate the Commonwealth Clean Oceans Plastics Campaign into the relay, focusing on ocean conservation and methods for recycling plastic waste.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The King's Baton Relay will culminate at the Opening Ceremony of Glasgow 2026 on 23 July 2026, as a traditional and fundamental part of the Commonwealth Games Opening Ceremonies.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] As part of the proposed plan put forward by Commonwealth Games Scotland, the opening and closing ceremonies are expected to be scaled down compared to previous Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It was announced on 20 March 2026 that the opening ceremony would take place at the OVO Hydro, the first time in the Games’ history that a ceremony will be held in an indoor venue.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It is unknown as of yet whether the closing ceremony will take place there or at another venue in Glasgow.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony will take place on 23 July 2026 at the OVO Hydro.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony will take place on 2 August 2026 which will include the formal handover to the next Commonwealth Games host city Ahmedabad, the Centenary Games in 2030.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] All 74 Commonwealth Games Associations are expected to participate in the 2026 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Gabon and Togo are expected to make their debuts since joining the Commonwealth of Nations in June 2022.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Given the urgency and lack of time to organise the event, this will be the lowest amount of sports offered at the Games since 1994.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Six of the included sports will include a Para sport element.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] These are Para Athletic, Para Track Cycling, 3x3 Wheelchair Basketball, Para Swimming, Para Bowls, and Para Powerlifting.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Sports dropped from the previous Games include rugby sevens, field hockey, badminton, triathlon, Twenty20 cricket, squash, diving, table tennis, beach volleyball, rhythmic gymnastics, and wrestling.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Of the full-sided team sports, only netball will be held, although the short-sided 3x3 versions of basketball are included.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Some outdoor public access events in retained sports such as athletics (marathons and race walking) and cycling (mountain bike and road cycling) were also dropped due to costs, while the bowls competition will be held in the indoor bowls format, rather than the traditional lawn bowls format.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Several sports programmes have received changes in their formats.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] In some cases, the number of quotas has increased, in other cases a new variety will be played for the first time.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The schedule was released on 31 July 2025.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The logo for the 2026 Commonwealth Games was described as a "historic first", integrating the Commonwealth Games Federation logo with the visual and institutional identity of the city of Glasgow.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It features symbolic representations of the River Clyde and the Clyde Arc bridge, interwoven within the Commonwealth Sport celebration mark, displayed in the colours of the waterfront.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] It was created by Glasgow-based agency Loop Design.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The official tartan for the 2026 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow was unveiled in July 2025 and created in collaboration with award-winning Scottish fashion designer Siobhan Mackenzie.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Registered with the Scottish Register of Tartans, the design incorporates the vivid blue, pink, and purple tones of Glasgow 2026 set against a steel grey base – a symbolic nod to the city's industrial heritage.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The tartan's thread count carries deeper meaning: 74 grey threads represent the number of participating nations and territories, while a bold blue thread count of 26 pays tribute to the year of the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The tartan will be produced in Scotland using local textiles and manufacturers.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The official mascot for the 2026 Commonwealth Games was scheduled to be unveiled on 23 July 2025, marking exactly one year until the start of the Games.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The mascot was designed by schoolchildren across Scotland, encouraging creativity and youth participation in the lead-up to the international sporting event.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Ahead of the announcement, promotional efforts included a light-hearted video released on 9 July 2025 featuring Clyde, the popular thistle mascot of the 2014 Commonwealth Games held in Glasgow.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] On 23 July 2025 the mascot of the games was announcement as Finnie, a Glaswegian unicorn.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] She is named after the city's Finnieston Crane and sports a traffic cone as her horn, referencing the custom of putting a traffic cone on Glasgow's Duke of Wellington statue.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] The unicorn is Scotland's national animal and supporter of the royal coat of arms of Scotland.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Scotland's reigning 10,000m Commonwealth Champion, Eilish McColgan, was announced as the first official Games Ambassador for the Glasgow 2026 Commonwealth Games on 21 July 2025.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Weightlifter Emily Campbell, gymnast Jake Jarman, wheelchair basketball player Robyn Love and swimmer Duncan Scott were all subsequently announced as Ambassadors.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Registration for 500,000 pre-sale tickets for the Commonwealth Games opened and will run until 16 October, giving priority to fans from the host city and country, with general public sales due to open on 30 October 2025.
[src:2026-commonwealth-games/2026-commonwealth-games] Tickets will be available from £26 for medal sessions and £17 for non-medal sessions, with concession tickets starting at £12.
